A MEMORIAL dedicated to antiwar campaigners has been unveiled at <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" target="_blank">Glasgow</a> GreenThe <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Monument" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Monument" target="_blank">monument</a> a black granite tablet set on a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/University_of_Colorado_at_Boulder" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/University_of_Colorado_at_Boulder" target="_blank">boulder</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bear" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Bear" target="_blank">bears</a> an <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Epigraphy" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Epigraphy" target="_blank">inscription</a> on a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Stainless_steel" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Stainless_steel" target="_blank">stainless steel</a> medallionIt reads &quotIn <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Memory" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Memory" target="_blank">memory</a> of those who opposed <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_War_I" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_War_I" target="_blank">WW1</a> in <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Religious_order" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Religious_order" target="_blank">order</a> to challenge the purpose of the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/War" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/War" target="_blank">war</a> and the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Waste" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Waste" target="_blank">waste</a> of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Parallel_Lives" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Parallel_Lives" target="_blank">lives</a>&quotThey also campaigned for <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Social" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Social" target="_blank">social</a> and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Social_justice" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Social_justice" target="_blank">economic justice</a> and against the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Exploitation" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Exploitation" target="_blank">exploitation</a> of those who lived in the city during the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/War" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/War" target="_blank">war</a>&quotThe <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Memorial" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Memorial" target="_blank">memorial</a> is situated directly behind the People's Palace near the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/International" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/International" target="_blank">International</a> Workers' MemorialIt was unveiled by <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lord_Provost" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lord_Provost" target="_blank">Lord Provost</a> Sadie Docherty on the 100th <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anniversary" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anniversary" target="_blank">anniversary</a> of the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" target="_blank">Women</a>'s Peace Congress which took <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" target="_blank">place</a> at The <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Hague" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Hague" target="_blank">Hague</a> in <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/April_22" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/April_22" target="_blank">April</a> 1915She said &quotOur <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/City_of_London" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/City_of_London" target="_blank">city</a> has commemorated the start of the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_War_I" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_War_I" target="_blank">First World War</a> and the many thousands of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People" target="_blank">people</a> who were <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Murder" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Murder" target="_blank">killed</a> and injured We have remembered them and their <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Suffering" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Suffering" target="_blank">suffering</a>&quotIt is also right that as part of our five <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/University" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/University" target="_blank">year</a> commemoration of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_War_I" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_War_I" target="_blank">World War I</a> the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/City_of_London" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/City_of_London" target="_blank">city</a> remembers those who tried to stop this devastating <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/War" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/War" target="_blank">war</a>&quotThey stood honourably against the great pressure of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/News_media" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/News_media" target="_blank">media</a> and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Public_opinion" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Public_opinion" target="_blank">public opinion</a> to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hundred_Days" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hundred_Days" target="_blank">campaign</a> for an end to the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/War" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/War" target="_blank">war</a> and the saving of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Parallel_Lives" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Parallel_Lives" target="_blank">lives</a> They are a part of our <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/History" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/History" target="_blank">history</a> and we must <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Respect" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Respect" target="_blank">respect</a> their points of view&quotSome of these antiwar campaigners are wellknown <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Name" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Name" target="_blank">names</a> who are <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Writing" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Writing" target="_blank">written</a> into our <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/History" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/History" target="_blank">history</a> like Jimmy Maxton <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Keir_Hardie" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Keir_Hardie" target="_blank">Keir Hardie</a> John Maclean John Wheatley  others including the great <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" target="_blank">women</a> campaigners are less known some only remembered by their <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Family" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Family" target="_blank">families</a>&quotThe great <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" target="_blank">Glasgow</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trio_%28music%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Trio_%28music%29" target="_blank">trio</a>  <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Helen_of_Troy" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Helen_of_Troy" target="_blank">Helen</a> Crawfurd Mary Barbour and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Agnes_Scott_College" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Agnes_Scott_College" target="_blank">Agnes</a> Dollan were outstanding <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Leadership" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Leadership" target="_blank">leaders</a> and the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" target="_blank">Women</a>'s Peace <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crusades" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crusades" target="_blank">Crusade</a> which they started spread far beyond <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" target="_blank">Glasgow</a>&quotHelen Crawfurd who was born in the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gorbals" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gorbals" target="_blank">Gorbals</a> and moved to Hyndland was a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Activism" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Activism" target="_blank">political activist</a> who along with her <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" target="_blank">Glasgow</a> born <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Friendship" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Friendship" target="_blank">friend</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Agnes_Scott_College" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Agnes_Scott_College" target="_blank">Agnes</a> Dollan attempted to actively involve <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" target="_blank">women</a> in the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Combat" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Combat" target="_blank">fight</a> against the warLast <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Week" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Week" target="_blank">week</a> former <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aberdeen" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aberdeen" target="_blank">Aberdeen</a> and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Manchester_United_F.C." title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Manchester_United_F.C." target="_blank">Manchester United</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Manager_%28professional_wrestling%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Manager_%28professional_wrestling%29" target="_blank">manager</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alex_Ferguson" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alex_Ferguson" target="_blank">Alex Ferguson</a> was in <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" target="_blank">Glasgow</a> to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Donation" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Donation" target="_blank">donate</a> &pound5000 to a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Fundraising" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Fundraising" target="_blank">fund</a> for a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Statue" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Statue" target="_blank">statue</a> to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mary_of_Teck" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mary_of_Teck" target="_blank">Mary</a> BarbourBarbour was a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Peace" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Peace" target="_blank">peace</a> campaigner who roused thousands of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Woman" target="_blank">women</a> to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Protest" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Protest" target="_blank">protest</a> at steep <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Renting" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Renting" target="_blank">rent</a> increases for <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Living_wage" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Living_wage" target="_blank">living</a> in <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" target="_blank">Glasgow</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Apartment" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Apartment" target="_blank">tenements</a> during WWIMrs Docherty said &quotThe antiwar campaigners also worked to protect the interests of the poor through the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Renting" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Renting" target="_blank">rent</a> strikes and the Clyde Workers Committee&quotHad their <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lead" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lead" target="_blank">lead</a> been followed so much <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Suffering" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Suffering" target="_blank">suffering</a> could have been prevented They deserve our <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Respect" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Respect" target="_blank">respect</a> and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Remembrance_Day" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Remembrance_Day" target="_blank">remembrance</a>&quot
